<P>
LANDING SITE WINDS MAY DELAY LAUNCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NASA fretted over the weather more than 4,000 miles away Wednesday night while 
preparing space shuttle Atlantis for launch today on an ozone-mapping mission. 
</P>
<P>
 Atlantis was scheduled to blast off at 8:56 a.m. PST. Good weather was 
expected at the space center, but clouds and high wind were forecast for the 
emergency landing sites in Spain and Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
 NASA cannot launch Atlantis unless at least one emergency landing site has 
acceptable weather. 
</P>
<P>
 This will be the fifth shuttle mission this year and the third in a row that 
is part of NASA's program to understand such environmental changes as ozone 
depletion and global warming. 
</P>
